  "prompt": "Why is goto discouraged?",
  "response": "The `goto` statement is discouraged in modern programming for several important reasons:\n\n1. Readability and Maintainability\n- Makes code difficult to read and understand\n- Creates \"spaghetti code\" with tangled control flow\n- Makes program logic hard to follow\n- Breaks logical structure of the code\n\n2. Structured Programming Principles\n- Violates principles of structured programming\n- Disrupts clean, hierarchical control flow\n- Can lead to complex, non-linear execution paths\n\n3. Error Prone\n- Easy to create infinite loops\n- Can skip important initialization or cleanup code\n- Makes debugging significantly more challenging\n- Creates potential for unexpected program behavior\n\n4. Modern Alternatives\n- Structured control statements (if, else, switch) are clearer\n- Functions and methods provide better code organization\n- Exception handling offers more robust error management\n- Loops (for, while) provide more predictable iteration\n\n5. Compiler and Optimization Challenges\n- Can interfere with compiler optimizations\n- Makes static code analysis more difficult\n- Reduces potential for performance improvements\n\nExample of problematic goto:\n```c\nint x = 0;\nstart:\n  if (x < 10) {\n    x++;\n    goto start;  // Potential infinite loop\n  }\n```\n\nBetter alternative:\n```c\nfor (int x = 0; x < 10; x++) {\n  // Clearer, more predictable iteration\n}\n```\n\nWhile some languages still support `goto`, it's generally considered a last resort.",
